The objects of travel are various. The excursions of the student through the world of letters are undertaken from different motives, and with different ends. That end may be either a rapid survey of general features, or a painstaking examination of particular obJects of interest. ‘⁶ It would be folly to attempt to lay down some pro- cess by which every man might ensure a main course of study for himself 3 but only let him have a just fear of desultory pursuits, and a wish for mental cultivation, and he may hope at some time or other to discern what it is fittest for him to do. And if he does not, but pursues anything with method‚ there will be some reward for him, if not the highest.’'†
